Ah, a classic calendar conundrum!  

270 days is a bit less than a full year, so we know the day of the week won't shift by too much.  Since there are 7 days in a week, I divide 270 by 7, which gives me 38 with a remainder of 4. That means 270 days is 38 full weeks plus 4 extra days.  

Starting on a Monday and adding 4 days brings us to Friday. 


\begin{center}
$\boxed{\text{Friday}}$
\end{center}

Ah, a system of congruences! These are quite straightforward once you understand the properties of modular arithmetic. 

Let's examine the given system:

\begin{align*}
&x-1\equiv 1-x\pmod {12},\\
&x-2\equiv 2-x\pmod{12}.
\end{align*}

Simplifying each congruence, we get:

\begin{align*}
&2x \equiv 2 \pmod{12},\\
&2x \equiv 4 \pmod{12}.
\end{align*}

Dividing both sides of each congruence by 2 (remembering that we can do this since 2 and 12 are relatively prime), we obtain:

\begin{align*}
&x \equiv 1 \pmod{6},\\
&x \equiv 2 \pmod{6}.
\end{align*}

These congruences tell us that $x$ leaves a remainder of 1 when divided by 6 in the first case and a remainder of 2 when divided by 6 in the second case.  Since these remainders are different, there are *no* integers that can satisfy both congruences simultaneously.


Therefore, there are $\boxed{0}$ solutions.

